<br>
1.62 - <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&quot;This is a very slippery slope. At this time, we're not planning on adding any more defense to skalds, although we do want to keep a close eye on this aspect and understand the concerns&quot;</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
1.64 - <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&quot;Right now we're not going to focus on skald defense. We might look into where their hit points stand, but even if a change was made here, the difference in hit point tenths between classes would be fairly minor and won't have a big impact on skald survivability&quot; </em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
1.64 - &quot;<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Parry - The only Speccable means of defense for the Skald is relegated to getting the leftover Spec points. A typical Skald will end up with a Parry of 17. Since we need to Spec high in Battlesongs and Weapon just to be competitive, we have to use RAs to balance out this spec. Lowering either Battlesong or Weapon does not return worthy results, even with the current changes to Parry/Block.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Feedback</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
--------------------------------------<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>I am willing to be convinced further, but right now I am not sure that trading weapon spec for parry isn't a valid option for skalds. I do agree that battlesongs is something most will want to keep high. </em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
--------------------------------------&quot;<br>
<br>
<br>
To summarise what I believe has been said is that the developers think that the amount of parry that could possibly be speced with evade 1 is a sufficient amount of defense with the other abilitys that can be used in a defensive nature in the Battlesong line to create a decent level of survivability for a melee focused class. Basicly this is just my thoughts on the issue (mostly old news to experienced Skalds).<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Specing for defence (Parry) and Evade</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Looking at spec choice possibilitys I dont believe tradeing either Battlesongs or Weapon for Parry creates a suitable return as with other classes for the following reasons. Firstly a Skald must at least have 44 in Battlesongs due to the double stacking nature of the Skald direct damage shouts. Missing out on the level 44DD means a drop of 18 levels on the &quot;Battle&quot; DD line to a level 26DD which is a significant drop in damage and a significant rise in resist rates (id guess around 50%) which is considered unexceptable on a timed spell. This is a fairly significant problem. The only way to counter this and spec in an alternate way while retaining a reasonable level of damage is to spec to 50 in Sword or Axe (the level 50 Hammer style is unsuitable for Skalds). However this creates its own problem as most if not all groups a Skald is invited to will expect a Skald to have the Heavenly Song of Travel spell (204% movement speed increase gained at 43 Battlesongs) which means the Skald is forced into a 50 Weapon, 43 Battlesong and 2 parry spec.<br>
<br>
The level 44 Weapon style is also highly desirable especialy for Axe and Hammer being the second part of a back positional chain and most Skalds consider it a &quot;must have&quot;. On Sword its not as important being the third part of a parry chain but even then missing out on the weapon skill gained from this is a problem especialy on a class with fairly mediocre weapon skill (and the style is occasionaly nice to). A 50 Dwarf Skald with RR5, + 10 strength at creation, + 75 strength item bonus and + 15 Weapon item bonus will have 978 weapon skill with 39 Weapon and 1011 with 44 Weapon ( a 3.5% increase roughly). <br>
<br>
The following specs are possible under this theory:<br>
<br>
39 Weapon (978ws), 44 Battlesongs and 29 Parry <br>
(29*0.5+5 = 19.5% parry chance) <br>
44 Weapon (1011ws), 44 Battlesongs and 21 Parry<br>
(21*0.5+5 = 15.5% parry chance)<br>
49 Weapon (1043ws), 44 Battlesongs and 4 Parry (4*0.5+5=7% parry chance)<br>
50 Weapon (1049ws) , 43 Battlesongs and 2 Parry<br>
(2*0.5+5 = 6% parry chance)<br>
<br>
With the range of effect increase of the 7.5 dps Damage adder in 1.65 indicated in the TL feedback we may also see these specs more often:<br>
<br>
44 Weapon (1011ws), 46 Battlesongs and 17 Parry <br>
(17*0.5+5 = 13.5% parry chance)<br>
47 Weapon (1030ws), 46 Battlesongs and 5 Parry <br>
(5*0.5+5 = 7.5% parry chance)<br>
<br>
*Note this is based on the research of others indicateing one point of Parry under level 50 is equal to 0.5% chance to parry and that there is a base possibility of 5% parry chance.<br>
<br>
Looking at these examples a player going for 39 in Weapon must give up roughly 3.5% weapon skill for only a 4% increase in chance to parry. The importance of parry and weapon skill is debateable but most Skalds feel that the weapon skill is worth considerably more than the parry chance given that weapon skill will be part of damage calculation (and I belive the enemies chance to succesfully defend the attack) every time the Skald hits an enemy with their weapon. Thus you see Skald templates like the 49 Weapon, 44 Battlesongs and 4 Parry that choose to ignore the parry spec possible in favour of more weapon skill as its such a small increase.<br>
<br>
Another reason for this choice to ignore Parry is that a Skalds dexterity, a statistic used in the parry chance calculation, does not rise with a Skalds level meaning that most Trolls will still have 35 dex, most Norse and Dwarves will still have 50 dex and most Kobolds will still have 70 dex meaning with item bonuses a Skalds dexterity will be at a base of between 110-145 at level 50. Again as damage and health points are considered more important in RvR compared to the perception of a weak defense system the majority of Skalds will put 10 points in strength, 10 points in constitution and 10 points in charisma at creation. These two facters combined mean that a Skald will have low dexterity in the parry chance formula and low dexterity and quickness in the evade forumla.  This is more of an issue for Skalds than most other classes with 1.5 spec and parry (Friar, Valewalker, Savage and Warden) as we have no way to augument our defences through any type of self buff,  no baseline buffs for soloing, no way to act outside of a fight beyond a very minimal effect and no reason to spend points into dexterity at creation as the weapon types we can use are based on strength not dexterity or a mix of strength and dexterity and apart from Parry the only thing effected by dexterity for a Skald is evade 1 compared to the evade 3+ on some of the mentioned classes.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Battlesong defensive abilities </strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
The &quot;defensive&quot; abilitys gained in the Battlesong line does little to help. The instant-single target mesmerise is fairly short duration (especialy when faceing high resist buffs and/or against anti-mesmerise/resist RAs and/or anti-mesmerise skills which is pretty common) and will often be automaticly resisted (which resets the recast timer) due to a mesmerise immunity from a Healers AOE mesmerise spell. The Snare is also of little help being of fairly low value (40%) and breaking on any damage.  Using it to escape from an opponent can often result in a high damage back positional attack or even a melee based stun or snare with a higher value then our own!  The resist chants are very difficult to use in an effective defensive manner given that they are 6 single line chants with one for each magic type so it is often very hard to have the correct magical type up for a certain spell being cast on you unless its a long battle against one enemy.  They tend to be used more in &quot;static&quot; situations such as a keep defense or siege where you know an enemy caster using a certain type magic of spell is present as a preventative measure or quickly switched on to fight a Hibernian or Albion PBAOE spell user.  Predicting other spell magic types in a &quot;fluid&quot; environment before they are cast is very very difficult.  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Weapon defensive abilities</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
The weapon styles gained by the Skald also do very little to help defensivly. Most of the inhibiting effects (stun or snare) that are useful defensivly tend to be from a parry or block reactional or positional which makes them very hard to use succesfully for the Skald or impractical in a face to face fight. They are also mostly of very short duration or high endurance cost.  The defensive bonuses in Skald weapon spec possibilitys are also either non existent or very lacking as well of being mainly of low to medium value. Perhaps this issue will be addressed in the style review though. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Other melee based hybrids defensive abilities</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Skalds would seem to be one of the least well equiped melee based hybrids in terms of defense for base or spec point defense:<br>
<br>
Skald (1.5 Spec points) - Chain armour (27%abs) + Evade 1 + Mesmerise shout + Parry + Resist chants<br>
Reaver (2.0 Spec points) - Chain armour (27%abs) + Evade 1 + DPS debuff shout + Large specable shield + Parry<br>
Paladin (2.0 spec points) - Plate armour (34%abs) + 56 AF self buff + 127 AF chant + Large specable shield + Endurance regeneration chant + Parry + resist chants<br>
Friar (1.5 Spec points) - Leather armour (10%abs) + 15% absorb self buff + 58 AF self buff + Evade 5 + Parry<br>
Valewalker (1.5 Spec points) - Cloth armour (0%abs) + 33%abs self buff + 250 AF self buff + Evade 4 + Parry<br>
Champion (2.0 Spec points) - Scale armour (26%abs) + str/con self buff + str/con debuff shout + dex/qui debuff shout + attack speed debuff shout + Evade 1 + Medium specable shield + Parry<br>
Thane (2.0 Spec points) - Chain armour (26%abs) + str/con buff + Medium specable shield + Parry<br>
Minstrel (1.5 spec points) - Chain armour (26%abs) + Evade 2 + Stun shout + Charmable pet + specable stealth + Ablative chant<br>
<br>
* Note some of these classes also get small unspecable shield<br>
<br>
The majority of these classes get either a high evade rate or medium/large specable shield as well as some other form of defense as part of their magical line. The Minstrel is the noteable exception lacking parry, high evade level or shield but gains a charmable pet, ablative chant, stun shout (rarely on an immunity timer due to Albions lack of AOE stun spells) and stealth in its spec lines.  Its a difficult class to compare given the fairly unique nature of its defensive abilitys but even then evade 2 and the dexterity gained while it levels is arguably as good as a Skalds evade 1 and small amount of parry modified by the Skalds low dexterity and quickness.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Realm abilities</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Although perhaps it should not be considered part of a classes ability the RAs available to a Skald are one of its few redeeming defensive features and are thus often used to balance out its lack of defensive base and speced abilitys.  Particuarly Avoid Pain and Armour of Faith are popular for the reason as it allows a Skald a better chance of surviving attention by an enemy melee.  The RAs focused on augumenting a Skalds base and speced abilitys however are not actually that popular.  Mastery of Parrying is rarely taken above one or two levels (and normaly at higher RR) due to the perception that Parry really doesnt help that much as it will still only be around a 25% parry chance at best (still modified by the low dexterity) and it only covers a frontal arc.  Mastery of Blocking is rarely if ever brought by Skalds due to the fact that small unspeced shield and a one handed weapon has a very niche use for a Skald (most will use two handed weapon exclusivly).  Really Dodger would seem a more appropriate RA for the Skald than Mastery of Blocking although it is not available.  Ignore Pain is more of a cure than a solution in most cases often being the only way a Skald will have a chance of beating a class with better defense as well as being hugely expensive when combined with its pre-requisites (23 points in total).  There are several other RAs that effect Skalds defense in a minor way but are not really major issues.  <br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Conclusion</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
In conclusion the Skald lacks in defense. Its support abilites dont allow it to effectivly act outside of a fight (or rather it contributes very little by doing so) and the majority of other hybrids and certainly the melee based tank, assasin and even archer classes have far greater defensive ability.  Low dexterity and quickness combined with &quot;forced&quot; low speced defense, low baseline defense and medium health points leave the Skald as one of the most vulnerable melee focused classes in the game.  While it is possible to supplement a Skalds defense to an exceptable level through RAs this is not really a satisfactory solution as it means the Skald will fall behind in other areas meaning that there is still an imbalance.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Possible survival improvement suggestions:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
1. An absorb self buff:<br>
<br>
Level 5 - 1% absorb<br>
Level 15 - 2% absorb<br>
Level 25 - 3% absorb<br>
Level 35 - 4% absorb<br>
Level 45 - 5% absorb<br>
<br>
2. Additional spec points (1.7 allowing for more parry)<br>
3. An AF self buff<br>
4. Additional hitpoints<br>
5. Higher evade and access to Dodger (remove Mastery of Blocking)<br>
6. Some sort of self castable proc (ablative, HoT proc etc) <br>
<br>
